# OSI Model vs TCP/IP Model

## OSI Model (7 Layers)

The OSI model is a conceptual framework that explains how data travels across a network.

- **Layer 7 – Application:** User-facing applications (HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SSH)
- **Layer 6 – Presentation:** Encryption, compression, data formatting
- **Layer 5 – Session:** Creates and manages communication sessions
- **Layer 4 – Transport:** Reliable communication using TCP/UDP
- **Layer 3 – Network:** Routing and IP addressing
- **Layer 2 – Data Link:** MAC addressing and error detection
- **Layer 1 – Physical:** Cables, switches, electrical signals

---

## TCP/IP Model (4 Layers)

The TCP/IP model is the practical networking model used on the Internet.

- **Application Layer** → HTTP, HTTPS, DNS, FTP, SSH
- **Transport Layer** → TCP, UDP
- **Internet Layer** → IP, ICMP, ARP
- **Network Access Layer** → Ethernet, Wi-Fi

---

# Protocol Placement

| Protocol | Layer |
|-----------|-------|
| HTTP | Application |
| HTTPS | Application |
| DNS | Application |
| FTP | Application |
| SSH | Application |
| TCP | Transport |
| UDP | Transport |
| IP | Internet |
| ICMP | Internet |
| ARP | Internet |
| Ethernet | Network Access |
| Wi-Fi | Network Access |

---

# Real Example

Example:

```
curl https://example.com
```

Communication Flow:

```
HTTP
   ↓
TCP
   ↓
IP
   ↓
Ethernet/Wi-Fi
```

This means an HTTP request is carried over TCP, which is transported using IP over the physical network.

